			<ns0:name>k...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/112873510090665368075/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Pair of zeros is "innocuous instruction" on IA32: it's "add %al,(%eax)". Pretty pointless yet harmless (since we are not doing data sandboxing there). So whole page filled with zeros is safe - we only need HLTs at the end of code region.

For x86-64 and ARM we rely on per-page protection anyway - if this does not work then the whole sandboxing is moot point.
